From e8337b819845fab424b399adc0d48cf2466b8c5f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 2026 01:23:13 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix timezone off-by-one date bug + remove committed .bak
 files

The onboarding date picker (and several other places) built local
calendar dates with date.toISOString().split('T')[0], which converts
to UTC. For users behind UTC (e.g. Toronto), once local time passes
~8-9pm, the UTC date has already rolled to the next day, causing the
stored date to be one day ahead of the displayed label.

Added src/utils/dateHelpers.js::getLocalDateString() which builds the
date string from local getFullYear/getMonth/getDate instead, and
replaced all 7 call sites (OnboardingFlow, DoctorReport,
SymptomHeatmap, App.jsx x2, dbService, mockData).

Verified with timezone-simulated tests reproducing the exact reported
bug (evening pick in America/Toronto) plus a UTC+ timezone control
case and a midday control case - all pass; old code fails the first.

Also removed server.js.bak and src/App.jsx.bak, leftover from a prior
security patch, which shouldn't be committed to the repo.
